title: Ed Guidelines & Ediquette
question: Important: Ed Guidelines & EdiquetteWelcome everyone!We‚Äôre excited to be your TAs this semester and hope you all are ready for a fun ride. We use Ed because it‚Äôs an incredibly valuable resource for students (ask questions, send updates/notices, etc.). In order to make Ed as efficient and effective as possible, we ask that you please follow these guidelines:BEFORE POSTING1. SEARCH BEFORE POSTINGBefore posting, please try to find if there are already similar Ed posts by searching one or two keywords related to your question and looking through our FAQ documents.2. Use other resources (lectures, textbook, other Ed posts, etc‚Ä¶) available to you before making a post on EdBefore you post on Ed, please take some time to attempt to debug and fully understand your problem. Using the resources and debugging techniques you have learned in office hours or recitation may allow you to answer your own question or make it easier for us to help you.DRAFTING POSTS3. DO NOT POST YOUR CODE PUBLICLYYou should never share your own code publicly. In general, try to refrain from posting code unless necessary. When appropriate, a TA may ask you to share your code privately to help answer your question(s).4. Format code using Ed‚Äôs code block formatFor readability purposes, if you are including code in a post please use the code block format (denoted by {;} symbol in the toolbar above the textbox). It should look like the following:let s : string = "Hello, World!" ;; print_endline(s) If the code is too long, feel free to attach a screenshot of your code complete with line numbers (make sure it is only visible to instructors).5. Use the folders!When making a post, organize it into the appropriate folder. This will help TAs and other students find your posts, and helps to keep things organized between assignments and exams.6. Be respectfulWe want everyone to have a great time in CIS1200 so please be respectful to course staff and your fellow classmates! Disrespectful posts will not be tolerated!AFTER POSTING7. Marking follow-ups as ‚Äúunresolved‚ÄùIf you post a question and decide later that you have a follow-up question, you can either edit your original post (only if you have not yet received a response) or post a followup question in the followup discussion section below your post.Please do not answer your own question with your followup question because this marks your question as resolved and the TAs will likely miss your question üò¶. On that note, if you post in the followup discussion section, do not forget to mark this discussion thread as unresolved!8. Gradescope and the TAs are not your debugger.We cannot help with failing Gradescope tests without a failing test of your own. When you submit homework on Gradescope, you will be given the name of the first failing test only. We cannot help you interpret the name or what it‚Äôs testing for, and we cannot tell you any information beyond that about other failing tests. If you fail a test on Gradescope, you will need to write your own tests for it before posting on Ed or coming to OH.9. Help your classmates!If you see a question and think you can answer it, please do! This‚Äôll help you learn the material as well!As always, please be respectful to your fellow classmates and CIS1200 staff. If you have any additional questions, feel free to let us know!Happy coding!

title: Office Hours Guidelines and Etiquette
question: Important: Office Hours Guidelines & EtiquetteOffice hours will start on Tuesday, September 2nd. Office hours for CIS1200 are often busy, so we publish these guidelines for TA office hours to ensure you are helped equitably and efficiently. TA office hours are in-person and you will use OHQ to join the queue in order to be helped.GuidelinesOffice hours are for conceptual and debugging help. Explain to your TA what you have already reviewed in terms of content or tried in terms of debugging. If you haven‚Äôt reviewed the lecture content or tried thoroughly debugging on your own, you‚Äôre not ready for additional help.Prepare for office hours. TAs will aim to spend five to ten minutes with you, so maximize the help you get by having clear questions prepared.If you do have a tough bug, your TA might ask other TAs to help debug or ask you to post on Ed. However, asking more TAs to help means longer wait times on the queue. Be respectful of your fellow students‚Äô time by having a clear and specific question in mind for your TA!If you encounter an unfamiliar bug, search Ed for related keywords. You will save yourself a lot of time spent debugging and waiting on the queue!As seen in the Ed guidelines, the TAs and Gradescope are not your debugger. If you fail a test on Gradescope, you must write your own failing test for a TA to be able to help you with your code.Recommendations and What to ExpectYou may already be familiar with OHQ, but here are some tips to ensure that everything goes smoothly and efficiently:Have a clear and specific question ready. Consider keeping a list of the things that you want to talk about with a TA.Continue to attempt to debug while you are in the queue. Sometimes students can find the bug before the TA gets to them!Here is what you should do when you‚Äôre with a TA:Describe your bug and the steps taken to produce it, or describe your conceptual question.Explain what you think the problem is and what steps you have taken to solve it. Do not simply say that something doesn‚Äôt work. We are here to help you learn how to debug effectively and think like a programmer ‚Äì not to do your assignment.Here is what to expect when the office hours queue gets long:Your TA may pass your question along to other TAs if it takes more than 10-15 minutes to help debug (this shouldn‚Äôt be the case if your question is clear and specific).When the queue is busy, we may enforce limits on how often students can ask questions in the queue. This prevents small numbers of students from occupying office hours at the exclusion of everyone else.We will clear the queue (remove any remaining questions from the queue) when scheduled office hours end.Looking forward to meeting many of you at office hours!

title: Encapsulation
question: Hi, I'm wondering if you have suggestions on how to remove swing from my game state class. I'm creating a typing game, and my game state class is called racetrack. This class is where I create objects that represent the player and the bot, and change their velocity, etc. I was using a keylistener to listen for what keys the user is typing and checking to see if the key they just typed is equal to the next character in my arraylist of characters:I'm also using a timer that goes off every few milliseconds and calls the tick() method to update the position of the bot and the player during the game:
answer: Ok, so to start - your model (RaceTrack) should not know anything about Swing. No Timers, KeyListeners, repaint, etc. Your model should expose simple methods that can be called by the controller, such as handleKeyPress(), tick(), isWinner(), etc. These are the methods that update positions/velocities and other game-state related stuff based on the current state. The UI view should handle key events / timer and call the model's functions with the relevant data as input. For example, a key listener in the UI view should parse the keypress or the position of the mouse click on the screen into data that can be passed into a move() function. (Ex: if your character could move left and right only, you could parse the keypress and have an if-else statement that calls move(String direction) with "LEFT " for "A" and "RIGHT" for "D". The keypress isn't exposed to the model, but you derive what it means before passing it in. These are just examples. So I would start by making another file and carefully separating the two functions. One file for the model (doesn't interact with Swing at all) and one file for the UI (calls the model functions based on user input).
all_answers: Ok, so to start - your model (RaceTrack) should not know anything about Swing. No Timers, KeyListeners, repaint, etc. Your model should expose simple methods that can be called by the controller, such as handleKeyPress(), tick(), isWinner(), etc. These are the methods that update positions/velocities and other game-state related stuff based on the current state. The UI view should handle key events / timer and call the model's functions with the relevant data as input. For example, a key listener in the UI view should parse the keypress or the position of the mouse click on the screen into data that can be passed into a move() function. (Ex: if your character could move left and right only, you could parse the keypress and have an if-else statement that calls move(String direction) with "LEFT " for "A" and "RIGHT" for "D". The keypress isn't exposed to the model, but you derive what it means before passing it in. These are just examples. So I would start by making another file and carefully separating the two functions. One file for the model (doesn't interact with Swing at all) and one file for the UI (calls the model functions based on user input).

title: getInstanceOf() vs getClass()
question: What is the difference? I checked lecture slides & recordings , but couldn't discern what the difference is as they both effectively look at the current dynamic class of a variable.Is it used when downcasting is not the optimal solution?
answer: instanceOf (I think that's what you're referring to) checks if the object is an instance of any object which it may inherit from/is in its inheritance tree, thus everything is an InstanceOf an Object. However, getClass just returns the dynamic class of the object. InstanceOf generally isn't preferable to use because it somewhat negates the benefits of polymorphism/inheritance. getClass is used primarily in cases like .equals where you must deal with the fact that to override you must write .equals so that it takes in an object, so you need to check to make sure it is the same class.
all_answers: instanceOf (I think that's what you're referring to) checks if the object is an instance of any object which it may inherit from/is in its inheritance tree, thus everything is an InstanceOf an Object. However, getClass just returns the dynamic class of the object. InstanceOf generally isn't preferable to use because it somewhat negates the benefits of polymorphism/inheritance. getClass is used primarily in cases like .equals where you must deal with the fact that to override you must write .equals so that it takes in an object, so you need to check to make sure it is the same class.

title: Tree Recursion
question: Is there an intuitive difference between the three. "In-Order" makes sense because if we're sorting an int tree, then the values at the numbered positions will correspond to the chronological order of the values.But I can't really understand pre-order or post-order intuitively? I have a hard time tracing the BST based on code alone, so would help if anybody has any 'tricks' or better explanations on this end.
answer: Knowing the specific terminology really isn't the most significant, rather just reading the code and recognizing the order and whether or not each branch gets evaluated.However, the easiest way for me to remember this is pre, in, and post represent the position where the root is evaluated, the the remaining two are left and right (with left always being first). So pre-order is root left right, in-order is left root right, post-order is left right root.
all_answers: Knowing the specific terminology really isn't the most significant, rather just reading the code and recognizing the order and whether or not each branch gets evaluated.However, the easiest way for me to remember this is pre, in, and post represent the position where the root is evaluated, the the remaining two are left and right (with left always being first). So pre-order is root left right, in-order is left root right, post-order is left right root.

title: Why don't we declare Runtime Exceptions and it's subtypes?
question: Title -- I rewatched the lectures and couldn't really discern why we differentiate b/w declared and undeclared exceptions. This question stems from the fact that I understand what to do, but not why we are doing it. Thank you!
answer: If every possible exception was declared (like RuntimeExceptions such as NullPointerException), every method that used something like an array would need to throw or try catch that exception because every array can throw it. This would make the code have a huge volume of try-catching and exception handling that isn't very helpful or necessary, especially because in a lot of cases runtime exceptions aren't things you want to happen at all so the code shouldn't continue, it should just stop. That's what the slide is referring to by lighter weight and easier to refactor code, it's much less dense code and classes/functions can be built much more easily.
all_answers:
If every possible exception was declared (like RuntimeExceptions such as NullPointerException), every method that used something like an array would need to throw or try catch that exception because every array can throw it. This would make the code have a huge volume of try-catching and exception handling that isn't very helpful or necessary, especially because in a lot of cases runtime exceptions aren't things you want to happen at all so the code shouldn't continue, it should just stop. That's what the slide is referring to by lighter weight and easier to refactor code, it's much less dense code and classes/functions can be built much more easily.

---

To add on, why would you want to catch and handle a NullPointerException? That would be very bad!! If your code is throwing a NullPointerException, that probably means you should stop running the program and fix it. Some exceptions are helpful when thrown! :)

title: 24fa final exam question 8.3
question: on the 2024 final fall, on question 8.3 where it asks what happens when you get rid of the repaint function in cookiepanel, the answer key says that the internal clickcount will update but depending on other various factors swing makes internally, the counter display may or may not change. How is this a logical answer as the code for updating the counter gui is in paintcomponent so without it, based on the given code, the gui should stay in the initial state and not update while the internal state updates (and this isnt even one of the answer choices).
answer: It's not saying you delete the repaint function, you just delete the call to repaint within the listener, so the paintComponent function is still there. Therefore, if the cookie panel is within a larger panel and repaint is called within the overall frame or a container of the cookie panel, then it will travel down to the cookie panel and call paintComponent on it as well, thus updating the cookie display. However, this isn't a guarantee that the cookie panel is within this larger group, thus other interactions/factors matter in whether or not it gets displayed.
all_answers: It's not saying you delete the repaint function, you just delete the call to repaint within the listener, so the paintComponent function is still there. Therefore, if the cookie panel is within a larger panel and repaint is called within the overall frame or a container of the cookie panel, then it will travel down to the cookie panel and call paintComponent on it as well, thus updating the cookie display. However, this isn't a guarantee that the cookie panel is within this larger group, thus other interactions/factors matter in whether or not it gets displayed.

title: ocaml structural and reference equality
question: 24fa: in ocaml if s == t is true then is s=t guaranteed to be true.the answer key says false but shouldnt it be true as if two variables point to the same reference on the heap then shouldnt they be structurally equal.
answer: Adding on, if you have a record of functions referred to as s and t, s == t will be true since they point to the same record but not s = t because structural equality between functions isn't defined/doesn't work.
all_answers:
It‚Äôs because if you use = to compare two recursive data structures, it could loop forever (think about comparing two cyclic queues). It could either hang or cause a stack overflow.

title: Simple Inheritance
question: I understand that simple inheritance for classes means you aren't overriding previous methods but does that mean that implementing an interface also counts as simple inheritance? What about interfaces extending other interfaces or multiple interfaces? Thanks
answer: Hi there.Good question!No, simple inheritance is only in the context of inheritance (when a class extends another class).When an interface extends another interface, there's no inheritance just interface extension so it wouldn't count as simple inheritance. Similarly, when a class implements an interface, there's no inheritance there either just interface implementation.Please let us know if you have any other questions.
all_answers: Hi there.Good question!No, simple inheritance is only in the context of inheritance (when a class extends another class).When an interface extends another interface, there's no inheritance just interface extension so it wouldn't count as simple inheritance. title: Tail Recursion
question: Why isn't this tail recursive from this semester's fall 25 midterm 2. My understanding of the concept is that as long as we don't need to "add something" or do an operation after we run the recursive call(i.e. 1+ mystery (x-1) is immediately not tail recursive or f mystery (x-1) where f is a function wouldn't be tail recursive). In this case, the lines are blurred, so I was deeply confused.
answer: the recursive calls to mystery(x-2) or mystery(x-3) both first depend on the result of mystery (x-1). Therefore, when the recursive call to mystery (x-1) is made, the stack space can't be cleared, meaning it's not a tail call.Your understanding is pretty accurate, the issue though is that you are doing an operation after the recursive call, either mystery (x-2) or mystery (x-3). I like thinking of it as you do, I also sometimes imagine it as traveling down the recursive calls and whether or not we know the answer of the initial call by the time we reach the base case or not. In this case, you don't, since the result of mystery (x-1) tells you whether or not you do mystery (x-2) or mystery(x-3) (and then you need to wait for that result).
all_answers: the recursive calls to mystery(x-2) or mystery(x-3) both first depend on the result of mystery (x-1). title: dynamic dispatch
question: could someone write out the distinction between what would cause the code to not compile vs. compile and throw an exception in a scenario of dynamic dispatch like this?
answer: The key fact here is that when we downcast, Java doesn't check at compile time if the dynamic type of the variable being downcast (JavaBarbie) is a subtype of the class being downcast to (OCamlBarbie). Thus, something like MattelToy barbie = new JavaBarbie() will compile, since MattelToy is a supertype of OCamlBarbie, so barbie could theoretically be dynamically a subtype of OCamlBarbie. However, it will throw a runtime exception. However, something like MattelToy barbie = new Object() won't compile, since Object isn't a subtype of MattelToy.
all_answers: The key fact here is that when we downcast, Java doesn't check at compile time if the dynamic type of the variable being downcast (JavaBarbie) is a subtype of the class being downcast to (OCamlBarbie). Thus, something like MattelToy barbie = new JavaBarbie() will compile, since MattelToy is a supertype of OCamlBarbie, so barbie could theoretically be dynamically a subtype of OCamlBarbie. However, it will throw a runtime exception. However, something like MattelToy barbie = new Object() won't compile, since Object isn't a subtype of MattelToy.

title: 23 fall qs 3
question: what does java generics invariant mean here? answer: No, the lecture notes explicitly say this is not possible.QueueImpl<Queue<String>> is a subtype of Queue<Queue<String>> but Queue<QueueImpl<String>> is not a subtype of Queue<Queue<String>>. title: sp24q
question: i can't really differentiate between what would cause encapsulation to be preserved vs. broken here. could someone explain it?
answer: The easiest way to understand it is that if you return an object that is internally stored in the class directly, i.e. without making a copy, you're breaking encapsulation because the user who used get can then intentionally or unintentionally modify the object in ways the class does not expect.So, returning currLetter and secretWord are fine because currLetter is a primitive (which are always pass by value, meaning a copy is made of them which gets returned), and strings are immutable. However, returning board[currGuess] returns the Letter[] array on the board. The user can reassign elements within this array to be null (so technically, even though an individual letter is immutable and thus can't be tampered with, which is the point of part k, an array of Letters can be tampered with, such as replacing one letter with another or with null).
all_answers: The easiest way to understand it is that if you return an object that is internally stored in the class directly, i.e. without making a copy, you're breaking encapsulation because the user who used get can then intentionally or unintentionally modify the object in ways the class does not expect.So, returning currLetter and secretWord are fine because currLetter is a primitive (which are always pass by value, meaning a copy is made of them which gets returned), and strings are immutable. However, returning board[currGuess] returns the Letter[] array on the board. title: is && and || tail recursive?
question: if I am calling a function in a pattern match is its just (conditional statement) && func ( params ) Is this tail recursive? what if the && switched for ||
answer: && and || don't automatically make something tail recursive. The key property is that &&and || are short-circuiting, meaning that if we can completely evaluate the left side of &&/||, we can reduce the whole expression to true/false/the right side of the expression. Thus, the expression is tail recursive if and only if the right side of the expression is tail recursive.
all_answers: && and || don't automatically make something tail recursive. The key property is that &&and || are short-circuiting, meaning that if we can completely evaluate the left side of &&/||, we can reduce the whole expression to true/false/the right side of the expression. Thus, the expression is tail recursive if and only if the right side of the expression is tail recursive.

title: 24 fall final 1.d
question: Can anyone explain why this is false? Thank you!
answer: All functions store their local variables on the stack.A non-tail-recursive function needs to perform additional work after the recursive call, so each call‚Äôs local variables, as well as workspace, remain on the stack until it returns. This causes the stack to grow and could potentially lead to a stack overflow.A tail-recursive function makes its recursive call as the last action, with nothing left to do afterward. This removes the need to store the workspace and pop the local variables, so each call uses constant stack space, effectively behaving like a loop (iteration).
all_answers: All functions store their local variables on the stack.A non-tail-recursive function needs to perform additional work after the recursive call, so each call‚Äôs local variables, as well as workspace, remain on the stack until it returns. This causes the stack to grow and could potentially lead to a stack overflow.A tail-recursive function makes its recursive call as the last action, with nothing left to do afterward. This removes the need to store the workspace and pop the local variables, so each call uses constant stack space, effectively behaving like a loop (iteration).
